ning and significance to the protagonists. The book includes consideration of a range of factors relevant to the choice of location for such events, and examines the declarations and motivations of political actors, from disaffected princes to independently minded nobles, as well as those who responded to rebellion, to show how places and landscapes became used in political disputes. These include both "public" and "private", religious, urban and rural space. Covering a long period in England and northern France, from the late Carolingian period through to the emergence of cross-Channel polities inthe aftermath of the Norman Conquest, this book casts valuable light on the political relations of the early and central Middle Ages. RYAN LAVELLE is Professor of Early Medieval History in the Department of History atthe University of Winchester.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGreat Britain-Politics and government-To 1485. 4aMedieval History. 4aMilitary History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aContested power.  aEngland.  aFrance.  aconflict.  aearly Middle Ages.  ahistorical perspective.  alandscape.  amedieval politics.  apolitical actors.  apolitical disputes.  apolitical relations.  arebellion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311143101740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787448018?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787448018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787448018/original  a978-3-11-143101-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles